          <p>1. Open <strong>geometrydash.ie</strong> in your browser and wait for the game to load completely. Make sure your sound is on to follow the music and rhythm. The game loads quickly and is ready to play within seconds.</p>
          
          <p>2. From the main menu, choose a level. Beginners should start with the first level to learn the basic jumps and obstacles before trying something harder. The early levels serve as tutorials for the game mechanics.</p>
          
          <p>3. Once the level starts, your cube moves automatically. Tap, click, or press the jump key to avoid spikes and holes. Focus on the beat and watch how the level reacts to the music. The soundtrack is not just for atmosphere—it directly relates to where obstacles appear.</p>
          
          <p>4. When you crash, the run restarts. Try to remember where you failed and prepare your jump a bit earlier next time. Each failure teaches you something new about the level. This is why practice mode is so valuable.</p>
          
          <p>5. Use practice mode when a level feels too difficult. In practice mode you can place checkpoints, so you do not need to restart from the very beginning after every mistake. This feature is essential for learning tough sections.</p>
          
          <h3>Controls and Input Methods</h3>
          <p>On PC, the default control is very simple: press the <strong>spacebar</strong>, click the <strong>left mouse button</strong>, or use the <strong>up arrow</strong> to jump. You only need one of these inputs; choose the one that feels most comfortable for you. Most players prefer the spacebar for keyboard play and mouse click for casual play.</p>
          
          <p>On mobile, tap anywhere on the screen to jump. The timing is the same, but your finger replaces the keyboard or mouse. Because the game is so responsive, even a tiny delay in your tap can be the difference between a clean jump and a crash. Mobile players often find it helpful to use headphones to hear the beat better.</p>
          
          <h3>Basic Rules and Game Flow</h3>
          <p>The rules of Geometry Dash are very clear: Your cube never stops moving forward. One mistake means instant death and restart. You win the level when you reach 100% progress. Practice mode lets you learn tough sections with checkpoints. There is no time limit, no lives counter, and no traditional "game over". You can try a level as many times as you want until you finally complete it.</p>
          
          <hr/>
          
          <h2>Tips and Tricks for Geometry Dash Success</h2>
          <p>Success in Geometry Dash is not only about fast reaction time. It also depends on patience, rhythm, and smart practice. Listen carefully to the music, watch the level patterns, and learn where each jump should happen. Here are proven strategies that will help you improve:</p>
          
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Do not spam jumps:</strong> Every tap should be intentional and timed. Unnecessary jumps often cause crashes.</li>
            <li><strong>Use headphones:</strong> Hearing the beat clearly helps you anticipate obstacles and time your jumps better.</li>
            <li><strong>Start with easier levels:</strong> Build your skills gradually before attempting the hardest levels.</li>
            <li><strong>Use practice mode extensively:</strong> Study sections that always kill you until you master them.</li>
            <li><strong>Take short breaks:</strong> Your focus will be better after a rest. Frustration leads to mistakes.</li>
            <li><strong>Watch your rhythm:</strong> The game is about following the beat, not just reacting to obstacles.</li>
            <li><strong>Learn from failures:</strong> Each crash teaches you something about the level design.</li>
            <li><strong>Customize your controls:</strong> Find the input method that feels most natural to you.</li>
          </ul>
          
